A potentially cancer-causing red dye was discovered in chilli powder used by Premium Foods to make Worcester Sauce, leading to the recall of over 350 food products in Britain.
The Food Standards Agency urged the public to return affected items for a refund and warned of a small risk of cancer.
The illegal dye Sudan I was found in various ready-made meals and sauces, prompting a widespread investigation.
The European Union and China also took action to prevent the spread of contaminated food.
Authorities advised against consuming tainted products and initiated a thorough examination of food sources.
